Logistic Regression & Support Vector Machine Models

Create a logistic regression model and a support vector machine model for the classification task involved with your dataset. Assess how well each model performs (use 80/20 training/testing split for your data). Adjust parameters of the models to make them more accurate. If your dataset size requires the use of stochastic gradient descent, then linear kernel only is fine to use.

Background

  • The problem for this analysis is the classification of used car price ranges based on Craig's list data. There are approximately 137,000 records in the data set.
  • There are seven price range categories for classification: <1K, 1K - 5K, 5K-10K, 10K-15K, 15K-30K, 30K-50K, and >50K.

Approach

  • Train and test the dataset for multi-class classification using Logistic Regression (LR) and Support Vector Machines (SVM). We also performed Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) with LR and SVM as well as LR with Principal Component Analysis (PCA).
  • Use GridSearch to determine the best parameters for Logistic Regression and SVM models.
  • Use four feature selection algorithms to determine the features that will go into the models: Random Forest, Extra Trees, KBest, and Recursive Feature Elimination Cross Validation (RFECV).
  • For SVM, a weighted sample of 30,000 was taken before running the models to reduce processing time.
  • Evaluate models based on the average accuracy, precision, and recall from 10-fold cross validation on train and test data with an 80/20 split using the StratifiedShuffleSplit method. The 'precision' and 'recall' are based on weighted averages.
  • The GridSearch (for both Logistic Regression and SVM) and RFECV take around 6 hours each to run on the entire data set. To save processing time for the final document, we saved the output of these algorithms to either static variables or csv files and used those to reproduce the results in the rest of the document. Thus, the code for these has been commented out in this notebook, but was previously run and the output saved.

Assessment

  • For SVM, the Top 60 features with RFECV had the highest metrics out of all the models with an accuracy of 70%, precision of 73%, and recall of 70%. The SVM models were run with 30,000 samples and not the entire data set to save time running the models. The run times were between 15-30 minutes per model with the sampled data. If time wasn't a constraint, it's possible the metrics might deteriorate using the full data set due to overfitting.
  • For Logistic Regression, the KBest features and Top 60 RFECV had the highest metrics with an accuracy of 62%, precision of 61%, and recall of 62% for models that used the entire data set. The run times were very short compared to SVM at around 2-3 minutes per model.
  • While the metrics for the best LR models are slightly lower than SVMs, the run time is significantly less even when the SVM models are run on a sampled data set.
  • In general, the metrics trend down as the number of features is reduced.
  • The metrics for SGD models are lower than other models, but have the fastest run time of all the models.
  • LR with PCA had the lowest metrics in the data set. We wanted to try it out, but it did not have good results.
  • KBest feature selection returned better results than Extra Trees and Random Forest selections.

Parameter Tuning

LR
For Logistic Regression, GridSearch was used to find the best values for C, max_iter, solver and tol. As the class to be predicted is multinomial, we used multi_class='multinomial', for reproducability - random_state=42.

GridSearch Results

  • C: 1000. The values tested were: [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100,1000]
  • max_iter=1000. The values tested were [100,500,1000]
  • solver='lbfgs'. The values tested were ['lbfgs','newton-cg']

    • SVM
    For SVM, GridSearch was used to find the best values for C and gamma. For the other parameters, some were specifically chosen and others left to the default values to help reduce the processing time.

    GridSearch Results

  • C: 100. The values tested were: 0.1, 1,10,100
  • gamma: 'auto'. The values tested were: 'auto','scaled'

    • Parameters Selected

  • kernel: 'rbf' was selected to get the support vectors
  • max_iter: Kept the default value of -1 for no limit. A GridSearch was originally done and 2000 was selected, but when the models had this setting, accuracy was significantly reduced. Although it did reduce the processing time by about 75%.
  • class_weight: Because the dataset has an uneven number of response values, 'balanced' was chosen to adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies.
  • decision_function_shape: this was set to 'ovo'. The documentation said that it would automatically be used for multi-class strategies.

    Default Values

  • degree, coef0: Did not apply or were not significant for 'rbf' kernels.
  • shrinking, probability, tol, cache_size: Left as default to save processing time. Further analysis or GridSearch on these parameters may improve the performance of the models.

    • Feature Selection

    • Random Forest: We are using Random Forest Classifier Feature Selection on all the feature variables. All the categorical variables were converted to binary using pandas one hot encoded and all the non-categorical variables were scaled using sklearn standard scaler. We are using random state =42 on this random forest classifier to keep consistent with the other algorithms. The chosen number of estimator for this random forest is 20 and output were sorted by highest impurity-based feature importances to lowest one,the higher value mean more important the feature. The top 3 features importances from this are odometer,car age in years and cylinders.
    • Xtra Trees: We are using a number of randomized decision trees a.k.a extra-trees Feature Selection as the next feature selection and it is on all the feature variables. All the categorical variables were converted to binary using pandas one hot encoded. We are using random state =42 on this classifier to keep consistent with the other algorithms. The number of estimators is set to 10. By sorting the output from the highest impurity-based feature importances to lowest one, the higher value mean more important the feature, the top 3 features importances are odometer,car age in years and cylinders.
    • KBest: We are using SelectKBest Feature Selection as the next feature selection and it is on all the feature variables. All the categorical variables were converted to binary using pandas one hot encoded. f_classif is chosen for the score function due to the needs of performing classification tasks on our dataset. The number of top features to select, k is set to 10. The higher the score value is the higher of feature importances. The top 3 features importances from this are odometer, car age in years and cylinders.
    • RFECV: We are using Recursive Feature Elimination Cross Validation (RFECV) as our next feature selection technique and it is run on all the feature variables. All the categorical variables were converted to binary using pandas one hot encoding. The parameter passed to this are: estimator = lr_clf. This holds the best model from logistic regression grid search.

      Step =1. One feature to remove on each run.
      CV = 10
      scoring = 'accuracy'
      The outputs assesed are:

      gridscores = The cross-validation scores such that gridscores[i] corresponds to the CV score of the i-th subset of features.
      ranking = The feature ranking, such that ranking[i] corresponds to the ranking position of the i-th feature. Selected (i.e., estimated best) features are assigned rank 1.

    Interpretation ¶

    Use the weights from logistic regression to interpret the importance of different features for the classification task. Explain your interpretation in detail. Why do you think some variables are more important?

    Although there are seven classifications for price range, the important features for cars 15,000 and under were similiar to each other as were those that are over 15,000. The interpretations are broken out into those two groups.

    Interpretation for the following price ranges:

    • Less than 1K
    • From 1K to 5K
    • From 5K to 10K
    • From 10K to 15K

    We can see from the below plot that the age of the car in years has most importance in determining whether the price of the car is less than 1K. This observation makes sense as we know that the value of a car depreciates with increasing age. The next most importance feature is odometer. Again, common knowledge tells us that the value of a car depreciates with increased mileage as it is a common indicator of wear and tear on a car. In other words, we can also say that there is correlation between age of cars and odometer as cars with higher age tend to have higher odometer readings. We can also see from the below plot that the price category of a car has negative correlation with cylinders and whether a car is a pickup truck or not. What these indicators are telling us is that it is rare to find a car less than 1K when it has higher number of cylinders or when it is a truck. Typically, higher number of cylinders is associated with premium / sports cars, which are not sold at such lower values in used car markets. Normally trucks have six or higher cylinders and therefore it makes sense to see that trucks are also negatively correlated with the price segment. The third feature worth mentioning is the drive type fwd. What we are seeing over here is that this feature plays an important role in predicting whether the price range. Manufacturer`s use forward wheel drives on most commuter / standard cars that also tend to be driven more. Starting from price ranges 1k we can see that there is a negative correlation between price ranges and whether a car is of type coupe or not. Typically, coupes are premium segment cars that are not sold at a lower price in used car markets. Finally, we want to comment that cars in this segment have a positive value for salvage indicator. This could be one of the factors why the price in this category.

    Interpretation for the following price ranges:

    • From 15k to 30K

    For car prices greater than 15K we can see that age and odometer have negative correlation with the price category. What this means is that these cars are new and have fewer miles on them, thereby commanding higher prices in the used car market. Another interesting observation is that the there is a positive correlation between cylinders and the price ranges. This reaffirms our understanding that we made before that higher cylinders are present in premium / sports cars or trucks that are bought at higher prices, thereby warranting higher prices in the used car market. We can also observer that for each of the three categories the variable type_new_pickup_truck is a positive number indicating presence of pickup trucks, thereby driving the price up as trucks are expensive. Also, we see that some cars in this segment are not run-on gas (fuel_gas is negative indicating absence of this indicator / encoded variable). This means that some of these cars in this price segment run on alternate fuel types. One explanation could be that higher cylinder cars tend to run on diesel / ethanol to increase the mileage. Finally, we want to comment that cars in this segment have a negative value for salvage indicator. This is an important factor as we know that salvage or cars with accidents have lower prices on the used car market.

    Support Vectors ¶

    Look at the chosen support vectors for the classification task. Do these provide any insight into the data? Explain. If you used stochastic gradient descent (and therefore did not explicitly solve for support vectors), try subsampling your data to train the SVC model then analyze the support vectors from the subsampled dataset.

    This plot shows the kernel density estimation (kde) for five of the important variables in the dataset: cylinders, car_Age_in_yrs, odometer, type_new_pickup_truck, and manufacturer_ford. The plots on the left show the kde for the ~17,000 instances chosen as support vectors while the plots on the right show the kde for the original dataset. The support vector lines are closer together because the data points form the decision boundaries between classes. The original data on the right has more variation because it represents the entire dataset.

    cylinders

  • The three peaks show a higher density for 4, 6, and 8 cylinder cars. The other cyclinders have a much lower density.
  • Cars in the 15-30K price range appear at the top of the plot for 4, 6, and 8 cyclinders and have the highest density between 0.4 - 0.5. They don't have the highest density in the original dataset so more vectors must be needed to create a good boundary.
  • The two lines near 0.2 are the kde's for cars less than 1K and greater than 50K. These two price ranges have the lowest number of support vectors. They also have low densities in the original dataset, except >50k cars is high for 8-cylinder cars and drops significantly for cars less than 1k.
  • The vectors for the three remaining ranges are fairly close to the 15-30K vectors, especially for 6-cylinder cars.

    • car_Age_in_yrs

  • All of the price ranges have a similiar shape.
  • Again, the pink and blue lines for cars less than 1K and >50K have the lowest density.
  • The peak for the pink line (>50K) is much higher in the original data than the support vectors. This must mean that fewer support vectors are required to create the decision boundary.
  • The blue line for cars less than 1k does the opposite. The support vector density is high at ~0.075 near the 7 year mark. Whereas in the original dataset, it stays around 0.05 between 1-20 years.

    • odometer

  • The density for all price ranges is above 6.0. Interestingly, the density for cars less than 1K peaks around 50,000 miles whereas the other price ranges peak above 100,000 miles. Looking at the original dataset, there seems to be a lot of overlap for that mileage with the other price ranges which could account for the higher density for that category.

    type_new_pickup_truck

  • This is a one hot encoded categorical variable. The bi-modal distributions of 0 and 1 are apparent. The 1s represent cars that are classified as a pickup truck. 0s are not pickup trucks and we can see that there are more of those represented here. For the 1s, the density is concentrated for support vectors ranging between 0.5 - 1.5.

    • manufacturer_ford

  • This is also a one hot encoded categorical variable where 1s are Fords. The plots are very similar between the original and support vectors. The main difference between them is that the density is condensed for the support vectors for the price ranges less than 1k and >50k.

    from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate

def EvaluateClassifierEstimator2(classifierEstimator, X, Y, cv):
    
    #Perform cross validation 
    from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_predict
    predictions = cross_val_predict(classifierEstimator, X, Y, cv=cv)
    
    #model evaluation 
    from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, accuracy_score
    
    #pass true test set values and predictions to classification_report
    classReport = classification_report(Y,predictions)
    confMat = confusion_matrix(Y,predictions)
    acc = accuracy_score(Y,predictions)
    
    print (classReport)
    print (confMat)
    print (acc)

    Recursive Feature Elimination Cross Validation¶

    We are using Recursive Feature Elimination Cross Validation (RFECV) as our next feature selection technique and it is run on all the feature variables. All the categorical variables were converted to binary using pandas one hot encoding. The parameter passed to this are: estimator = lr_clf. This holds the best model from logistic regression grid search. Step =1. One feature to remove on each run. CV = 10 scoring = 'accuracy' The outputs assesed are: gridscores = The cross-validation scores such that gridscores[i] corresponds to the CV score of the i-th subset of features. ranking = The feature ranking, such that ranking[i] corresponds to the ranking position of the i-th feature. Selected (i.e., estimated best) features are assigned rank 1.

    In [165]:
    #create an estimator for scoring
#reference for Dr. Drew's code: https://nbviewer.jupyter.org/github/jakemdrew/EducationDataNC/blob/master/2017/Models/2017ComparingSegregatedHighSchoolCampuses.ipynb
def EvaluateClassifierEstimator(classifierEstimator, X, y, cv, score_params):
   
    #Perform cross validation 
    scores = cross_validate(classifierEstimator, X, y, scoring=score_params, cv=cv, return_train_score=True)

    Accavg = scores['test_accuracy'].mean()
    Preavg = scores['test_precision'].mean()
    Recavg = scores['test_recall'].mean()

    print_str = "The average accuracy for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {Accavg:.5}"
    print_str2 = "The average precision for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {Preavg:.5}"
    print_str3 = "The average recall for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {Recavg:.5}"

    print(print_str.format(Accavg=Accavg))
    print(print_str2.format(Preavg=Preavg))
    print(print_str3.format(Recavg=Recavg))
    print('*********************************************************')

    print('Cross Validation Fold Mean Error Scores')
    scoresResults = pd.DataFrame()
    scoresResults['Accuracy'] = scores['test_accuracy']
    scoresResults['Precision'] = scores['test_precision']
    scoresResults['Recall'] = scores['test_recall']

    return scoresResults

#reference:  https://nbviewer.jupyter.org/github/jakemdrew/DataMiningNotebooks/blob/master/04.%20Logits%20and%20SVM.ipynb

#use the cv object to iterate through different training and testing sets. Each time we will reuse the svm
#object, but it gets trained on different data each time we use it.
iter_num=0
for train_idx, test_idx in cv.split(X_30k,y_30k):
    svm_clf3.fit(scl.fit_transform(X_30k[train_idx]),y_30k[train_idx])
    y_hat3 = svm_clf3.predict(scl.fit_transform(X_30k[test_idx]))
    acc3= mt.accuracy_score(y_30k[test_idx],y_hat3)
    conf3= mt.confusion_matrix(y_30k[test_idx],y_hat3)
    print("====Iteration",iter_num," ====")
    print("accuracy", acc3)
    print("confusion matrix\n",conf3)
    print(classification_report(y_30k[test_idx], y_hat3, zero_division=0))
    iter_num+=1
